ce:section.ce:para:
The UV/Vis spectra was used to characterize all the complexes (1,2). The Soret band for complex 1 Soret band was observed at 428 nm with four Q-bands. Following metalation of complex 1 with Sn(IV)chloride to give complex 2, the Soret band was observed at 434 nm (Table 1
                        ) whereby it red shifted by 6 nm and the four Q-bands merged into two, Fig. 1
                        A. Introduction of heavy metals results in degree of perturbation and electron delocalisation within the porphyrin macrocycle, resulting in red shift of the Soret band [22]. The fluorescence for complex 2 was very weak due to presence of the heavy central metal (Sn(IV)) which encourages intersystem crossing to the triplet state, quenching fluorescence [23,24].
